1 Introduction
**************

Eve is an Emacs major mode for editing spoken-word videos by
manipulating text instead of cutting timelines manually.

* Menu:

* The Big Idea::
* The Core Workflow::
* About This Manual::


File: eve.info,  Node: The Big Idea,  Next: The Core Workflow,  Up: Introduction

1.1 The Big Idea
================

Traditional video editing works at the frame level: you scrub a
timeline, find a cut point, and trim.  When your source material is a
talking-head recording or a podcast, almost every edit decision is
driven by what was _said_ — not by what is visible.

   Eve flips the model.  A Textual Join Manifest (‘.tjm.json’) stores
your video as a sequence of transcribed segments, each with per-word
timestamps.  You read and edit the transcript in Emacs.  Delete a word,
and it disappears from the rendered video.  Reorder paragraphs, and the
clips follow.  Annotate a segment with a b-roll clip, and the renderer
splices it in.  The text is the edit.


File: eve.info,  Node: The Core Workflow,  Next: About This Manual,  Prev: The Big Idea,  Up: Introduction

1.2 The Core Workflow
=====================

The typical eve session looks like this:

  1. *Transcribe* — run ‘M-x eve-transcribe’ on a directory of raw
     recordings.  Eve calls ‘eve transcribe’ and opens the resulting
     ‘.tjm.json’ in eve-mode.

  2. *Edit* — delete filler words (‘d’, ‘f’, ‘F’), reorder segments
     (‘J’, ‘K’), add markers to name sections (‘o’), attach b-roll
     (‘b’).

  3. *Preview* — press ‘C-c SPC’ to play the source clip from point, or
     ‘C-c C-c’ to compile a draft video in seconds.

  4. *Compile* — ‘C-c C-c’ renders the manifest as an ‘.mp4’.  Draft
     renders are fast (mjpeg, parallel, cached).  ‘C-u C-c C-c’ produces
     a final delivery-quality H.264 export.

  5. *Iterate* — the segment cache means only changed segments
     re-encode.  Speculative pre-rendering warms the cache on every
     save, so pressing ‘C-c C-c’ after a small edit is nearly instant.


File: eve.info,  Node: About This Manual,  Prev: The Core Workflow,  Up: Introduction

