File: eve.info,  Node: Deletion and restoration,  Next: Splitting and merging,  Prev: Navigation,  Up: Editing

5.2 Deletion and restoration
============================

   • ‘d’ (‘eve-delete-word’) — marks the word at point as deleted.
     Deleted words are hidden in the buffer (‘eve-hide-deleted-mode’)
     and excluded from compilation.  The operation is non-destructive:
     the word remains in the JSON and can be restored.

   • ‘D’ (‘eve-delete-segment’) — marks the entire current segment as
     deleted.

   Deleted content is shown or hidden with ‘C-c C-h’
(‘eve-hide-deleted-mode’).


File: eve.info,  Node: Splitting and merging,  Next: Reordering,  Prev: Deletion and restoration,  Up: Editing

5.3 Splitting and merging
=========================

   • ‘s’ or ‘|’ (‘eve-split-segment’) — splits the current segment at
     point, creating two segments with the text and timing divided at
     the cut.

   • ‘m’ or ‘)’ (‘eve-merge-with-next’) — merges the current segment
     with the one below, combining text and adjusting the end time.


File: eve.info,  Node: Reordering,  Next: Markers and sections,  Prev: Splitting and merging,  Up: Editing

5.4 Reordering
==============

   • ‘J’ (‘eve-move-segment-down’) — move the current segment one
     position down.
   • ‘K’ (‘eve-move-segment-up’) — move the current segment one position
     up.


File: eve.info,  Node: Markers and sections,  Next: Inline editing,  Prev: Reordering,  Up: Editing

5.5 Markers and sections
========================

Press ‘o’ (‘eve-insert-marker’) to insert a marker above the current
segment.  Markers act as named section headings.  They appear in the
buffer as bold titles.

   When you compile with ‘C-c C-c’ while point is on a marker, only the
segments in that section are compiled.  This is useful for working on
one chapter of a longer video.


File: eve.info,  Node: Inline editing,  Next: Metadata,  Prev: Markers and sections,  Up: Editing

5.6 Inline editing
==================

Press ‘e’ (‘eve-dwim-edit’) to edit the text or metadata of the segment
at point.  The command adapts to context: on a word it edits the spoken
text; on a marker it edits the title.


File: eve.info,  Node: Metadata,  Next: Undo and redo,  Prev: Inline editing,  Up: Editing

5.7 Metadata
============

Key         Command                Description
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
‘t’         ‘eve-toggle-tag’       Toggle a tag on the segment at point.
‘i’         ‘eve-edit-speaker’     Set the speaker label for the segment.
‘r’         ‘eve-edit-start-end’   Edit the segment's start/end timecodes.
‘C-c C-n’   ‘eve-edit-notes’       Edit free-form notes for the segment.


File: eve.info,  Node: Undo and redo,  Next: Validation,  Prev: Metadata,  Up: Editing

5.8 Undo and redo
=================

   • ‘u’ (‘eve-undo’) — undo the last edit.
   • ‘C-r’ (‘eve-redo’) — redo a previously undone edit.

   Eve maintains its own undo stack separate from Emacs's built-in undo.


File: eve.info,  Node: Validation,  Prev: Undo and redo,  Up: Editing

5.9 Validation
==============

Eve validates the manifest automatically on every save (controlled by
‘eve-validation-on-save’).  Manual validation runs with ‘C-c C-v’
(‘eve-validate’).  Timing inconsistencies are reported in the echo area.


