7.5.1 Overlay fields
--------------------

Each overlay in the ‘overlays’ array supports:

Field                                     Description
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
‘placeholder’                             Name of the placeholder key this overlay renders.
‘fontsize’ (or ‘size’)                    Font size in pixels.
‘color’ (or ‘fontColor’)                  Font colour (ffmpeg colour syntax: name, ‘#rrggbb’, ‘white@0.8’).
‘x’ (or ‘position_x’)                     Horizontal position (pixels or ffmpeg expression like ‘(w-text_w)/2’).
‘y’ (or ‘position_y’)                     Vertical position (pixels or ffmpeg expression).
‘align’                                   Set to ‘"center"’ to auto-centre horizontally and vertically.
‘font’ (or ‘fontfile’)                    Path to a ‘.ttf’ or ‘.otf’ font file.
‘boxColor’ (or ‘box_color’)               Background box colour (e.g.  ‘black@0.6’ for 60% opacity).
‘shadowColor’ / ‘shadow_x’ / ‘shadow_y’   Drop shadow parameters.
‘start’ / ‘end’ / ‘duration’              Time window (seconds) during which the overlay is visible.


File: eve.info,  Node: Concrete example lower-third title card,  Prev: Overlay fields,  Up: JSON templates

7.5.2 Concrete example: lower-third title card
----------------------------------------------

Suppose you have a background image ‘lower-third.png’ and you want to
show the speaker's name and title during a segment.

  1. Create the template file ‘assets/lower-third.json’:

          {
            "template": "assets/lower-third.png",
            "overlays": [
              {
                "placeholder": "NAME",
                "fontsize": 42,
                "color": "white",
                "x": 80,
                "y": 620,
                "font": "assets/Inter-Bold.ttf",
                "boxColor": "black@0.5"
              },
              {
                "placeholder": "ROLE",
                "fontsize": 28,
                "color": "#cccccc",
                "x": 80,
                "y": 672,
                "font": "assets/Inter-Regular.ttf"
              }
            ],
            "placeholders": {
              "NAME": "Speaker Name",
              "ROLE": "Speaker Role"
            }
          }

  2. In eve-mode, press ‘b’ on the segment where you want the title
     card.  Set ‘file’ to ‘assets/lower-third.json’.  Set ‘mode’ to
     ‘replace’.

  3. Press ‘C-c C-b’ to edit placeholders for this segment:

          Placeholder NAME (default Speaker Name): Jane Doe
          Placeholder ROLE (default Speaker Role): Product Lead
          New placeholder key (blank to finish):

  4. Compile with ‘C-c C-c’.  The rendered segment shows
     ‘lower-third.png’ with "Jane Doe" and "Product Lead" burned in as
     text overlays at the specified positions and sizes.

   Each segment can override different placeholder values from the same
template.  The template is reused; only the text changes.


File: eve.info,  Node: Placeholders without templates,  Next: Continuation chains,  Prev: JSON templates,  Up: B-Roll

7.6 Placeholders without templates
==================================

You can also set placeholder key-value pairs directly on a segment
without a JSON template, using ‘C-c C-b’.  These are stored in the
manifest under ‘edit.broll.placeholders’ and are available for any
overlay definitions.


File: eve.info,  Node: Continuation chains,  Prev: Placeholders without templates,  Up: B-Roll

7.7 Continuation chains
=======================

When a single b-roll clip should span multiple consecutive segments, use
continuation chains:

  1. Press ‘b’ on the first segment and configure the b-roll normally.
  2. Move to the next segment and press ‘B’
     (‘eve-toggle-broll-continue’).

   ‘B’ copies the b-roll metadata from the nearest preceding segment
that has b-roll, then auto-calculates:

   • ‘continue’: set to ‘true’.
   • ‘start_offset’: previous offset + previous segment duration, so
     playback continues seamlessly from where the last segment left off.
   • ‘duration’: remaining duration of the b-roll clip (if the original
     had a duration set).

   Repeat ‘B’ on each subsequent segment in the chain.  The renderer
treats the entire chain as one continuous b-roll playback — the clip
advances smoothly across segment boundaries without restarting.


